        <span class="k-link k-state-selected">Question @Model?.Id</span>
        <div>
            <p>
                @Html.Raw(Model.H1OpenTag)
                You have an Azure resource group named RG1. RG1 contains a Windows Server 2012 R2 virtual machine (VM) named VM1.
                @Html.Raw(Model.H1CloseTag)
            </p>
            <p>
                @Html.Raw(Model.H2OpenTag)
                You plan to use Azure Cloud Shell and Azure PowerShell to configure backup for VM1.
                @Html.Raw(Model.H2CloseTag)
            </p>
            <p>
                You need to ensure that Azure uses geo-redundant storage for the backups.
            </p>
            <p>
                How should you complete the Azure PowerShell command? To answer, select the appropriate options from the drop-down menus.
            </p>
        </div>
    </li>
    <li class="k-state-active">
        Answers
        TO DO
    </li>
    <li>
        Explanation
        <div>
            <p>
                You should use the following command:
            </p>
            <p>
                $t = Get-AzureRmRecoveryServicesVault -Name "t1"
                <br />
                Set-AzureRmRecoveryServicesBackupProperties -Vault $t
                <br />
                -BackupStorageRedundancy GeoRedundant
            </p>
            <p>
                To configure your Recovery Services vault to use geo-redundant backup programmatically with Azure PowerShell, you should start with the Get-AzureRmRecoveryServicesVault cmdlet to retrieve the correct vault.
            </p>
            <p>
                You should not use the Get-AzureRmStorageAccount or Set-AzureRmStorageAccount cmdlets because VM backup with Recovery Services vaults does not require separate storage accounts.
            </p>
            <p>
                Next, run the Set-AzureRmRecoveryServicesBackupProperties cmdlet with the -BackupStorageRedundancy parameter to complete the configuration. The other valid parameter value is LocallyRedundant, which configures the vault to use locally redundant (LRS) storage.
            </p>
            <p>
                You should not run the -SkuName parameter of the Set-AzureRmStorageAccount cmdlet because this scenario deals with Recovery Services vaults and not storage accounts. When used with storage accounts, the -SkuName parameter allows you to specify a replication level for the storage account.
            </p>
        </div>
